<body>
  <div class="container">
    <h1>Car Steering System Guide</h1>

    <!-- Purpose Section -->
    <div class="card">
      <h2>Purpose</h2>
      <p>The steering system is a critical component of a vehicle, allowing the driver to control the direction of the wheels. It ensures smooth and precise handling, making driving safe and comfortable.</p>
    </div>

    <!-- Types of Steering Systems Section -->
    <div class="card">
      <h2>Types of Steering Systems</h2>
      <ul>
        <li><strong>Manual Steering:</strong> Relies on the driver's physical effort to turn the wheels. Common in older vehicles.</li>
        <li><strong>Power Steering:</strong> Uses hydraulic or electric assistance to reduce the effort required to steer the vehicle.</li>
        <li><strong>Electric Power Steering (EPS):</strong> Uses an electric motor to assist steering, offering better fuel efficiency and control.</li>
        <li><strong>Hydraulic Power Steering:</strong> Uses hydraulic fluid to assist steering, providing a smooth and responsive feel.</li>
      </ul>
    </div>

    <!-- Components Section -->
    <div class="card">
      <h2>Components</h2>
      <ul>
        <li><strong>Steering Wheel:</strong> The interface through which the driver controls the direction of the vehicle.</li>
        <li><strong>Steering Column:</strong> Connects the steering wheel to the steering mechanism.</li>
        <li><strong>Steering Gearbox:</strong> Converts the rotational motion of the steering wheel into the linear motion needed to turn the wheels.</li>
        <li><strong>Tie Rods:</strong> Connect the steering gear to the wheels, transmitting the steering force.</li>
        <li><strong>Power Steering Pump:</strong> Provides hydraulic pressure to assist steering in hydraulic systems.</li>
      </ul>
    </div>

    <!-- Maintenance Section -->
    <div class="card">
      <h2>Maintenance</h2>
      <ul>
        <li>Regularly check the power steering fluid level and top it up if necessary.</li>
        <li>Inspect the steering system for leaks, especially in hydraulic systems.</li>
        <li>Ensure the steering wheel alignment is correct to prevent uneven tire wear.</li>
        <li>Lubricate steering components to reduce friction and wear.</li>
        <li>Listen for unusual noises (e.g., squeaking or grinding) that may indicate steering system issues.</li>
      </ul>
    </div>

    <!-- Signs of Steering Issues Section -->
    <div class="card">
      <h2>Signs of Steering Issues</h2>
      <ul>
        <li><strong>Difficulty Turning:</strong> Increased effort required to turn the steering wheel.</li>
        <li><strong>Steering Wheel Vibration:</strong> Shaking or vibrating steering wheel, especially at high speeds.</li>
        <li><strong>Unresponsive Steering:</strong> Delayed or loose response when turning the wheel.</li>
        <li><strong>Noises:</strong> Squeaking, grinding, or clunking sounds when steering.</li>
        <li><strong>Fluid Leaks:</strong> Visible power steering fluid leaks under the vehicle.</li>
      </ul>
    </div>

    <!-- Images Section -->
